│ visitExtractValueInst currently:                                              │
│ - Checks that Op (EVI’s operand) is a struct-of-matching-fixed-vectors        │
│ produced by a trivially scalarizable intrinsic.                               │
│ - Derives VecType as the first contained vector type of the struct.           │
│ - Calls scatter(&EVI, Op, *VS) using the VectorSplit for VecType, but Op is   │
│ still the struct, not the vector.                                             │
│ - Then, for each fragment, does CreateExtractValue(Op0[OpIdx], Index...).     │
│ This is inconsistent: scatter is documented to work on a vector or            │
│ pointer-to-vector, not on a struct. Passing the struct causes                 │
│ Scatterer::operator[] to try to extract elements from a non-vector Value,     │
│ ultimately calling CreateExtractElement(V, ...), where V is a struct,         │
│ crashing the cast.                                                            │
│ The intended operation for extractvalue on a struct-of-vectors is: first      │
│ extract the selected struct field (vector), then scatter that vector, and     │
│ then each fragment is directly the result (no further extractvalue from       │
│ fragments).                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ Edit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/Scalarizer.cpp lines 1065-1098 (in       │
│ visitExtractValueInst) to:                                                    │
│ - First extract the requested struct field into a vector Value using          │
│ CreateExtractValue(Op, Index).                                                │
│ - Scatter that extracted vector (not the original struct) with the computed   │
│ VectorSplit.                                                                  │
│ - Populate Res with the fragments returned from the scatter directly, without │
│ creating another ExtractValue on them.                                        │
│ Concretely, replace:                                                          │
│   IRBuilder<> Builder(&EVI);                                                  │
│   Scatterer Op0 = scatter(&EVI, Op, *VS);                                     │
│   assert(!EVI.getIndices().empty() && "Make sure an index exists");           │
│   unsigned Index = EVI.getIndices()[0];                                       │
│   for (unsigned OpIdx = 0; OpIdx < Op0.size(); ++OpIdx) {                     │
│     Value *ResElem = Builder.CreateExtractValue(                              │
│         Op0[OpIdx], Index, EVI.getName() + ".elem" + Twine(Index));           │
│     Res.push_back(ResElem);                                                   │
│   }                                                                           │
│ with:                                                                         │
│   IRBuilder<> Builder(&EVI);                                                  │
│   assert(!EVI.getIndices().empty() && "Make sure an index exists");           │
│   unsigned Index = EVI.getIndices()[0];                                       │
│   // First extract the selected vector component from the struct.             │
│   Value *Vec = Builder.CreateExtractValue(Op, Index, EVI.getName() + ".elem"  │
│ + Twine(Index));                                                              │
│   // Now scatter the extracted vector into its fragments.                     │
│   Scatterer Op0 = scatter(&EVI, Vec, *VS);                                    │
│   for (unsigned OpIdx = 0; OpIdx < Op0.size(); ++OpIdx)                       │
│     Res.push_back(Op0[OpIdx]);                                                │
│ This ensures scatter receives a vector Value and avoids the invalid           │
│ CreateExtractElement on a struct.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By extracting the chosen struct field into a vector before scattering,        │
│ Scalarizer operates on the correct type and the crash is eliminated. The      │
│ result fragments are directly the components of the extracted vector, so no   │
│ further ExtractValue is needed. This fix aligns visitExtractValueInst with    │
│ its intent to scalarize trivially scalarizable intrinsics returning structs   │
│ of vectors, and prevents the assertion failure in ExtractElementInst.         │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
